<HEADLINE>
FT  21 NOV 94 / This Week: Big clubs push the panic button - Sport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEITH WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It has, observes Terry Butcher, been like August 12 - with soccer managers
gunned down rather than grouse. From his new role as a hotelier in the
Scottish hills, where they know how to shoot, Butcher, former England
captain and sometime league manager, has observed the slaughter.
Mike Walker at Everton, Ossie Ardiles of Spurs, Ron Atkinson from Aston
Villa. 'Look at Atkinson. Won the Coca-Cola Cup last season. Took the team
into Europe and now he's fired after a few bad results,' says Butcher,
himself tin-tacked from Sunderland before embarking on a new life as mine
host at the Old Manor Hotel, Bridge of Allen. 'There isn't a manager in
England who isn't worried about next week.'
So what's new? In terms of job security, the British soccer manager and the
Colosseum gladiator would have had much in common. 'It's always been
precarious,' agrees John Camkin, secretary of the League Managers'
Association (LMA). 'But without a doubt we're seeing something completely
new here, to have big-name sackings in such numbers.' Panic is the new
factor. According to Camkin, and virtually everyone else in the game, the
financial gap between the Premiership and Division One is now so great that
club chairmen are terrified of dropping down and never being seen again.
This season, four clubs will be relegated to a soccer netherworld, where Sky
TV's money doesn't reach and Manchester United never visit. 'It's straight
down into the polar regions, in terms of crowds, money and resources. It's
an unbelievable difference,' says Butcher. For a club with high fixed
overheads, staying among the elite is not just about a place in the sun.
It's about survival.
'If you were to drop out of the Premiership, a lot of revenue streams turn
down simultaneously,' says Steven Kind, chief accountant at Leicester City
(themselves currently in the worry zone). 'As well as smaller gates, you'd
have to look at the ticket pricing structure. In Division One, where we were
last season, it would be a struggle to keep the same number of season
ticket-holders. You'd have to re-assess the whole running of City.'
A 'Foxes' season ticket currently costs Pounds 340, 30 per cent higher than
last year, when they were in the lower division. Sky TV revenues will form
around 13 per cent of the club's expected Pounds 6m-plus turnover this
season, whereas Division One is covered by ITV, which pays nothing like as
much.
Official statistics for English league soccer as a whole show an average
Premiership gate this season of 23,375. For Endsleigh Division One the
comparable figure is 10,567. Probably the biggest fixed cost for a club is
the players' wages bill. In the old First Division, two seasons ago, the
weekly average wage was Pounds 1,152. Now the Premiership estimates a figure
of Pounds 2,500, and that conceals some startling variations. Jurgen
Klinsmann at Spurs is said to be the highest-paid player in British soccer,
earning Pounds 12,000 a week. If the club goes down, the wage bill doesn't.
'In any normal business, personnel are not a fixed overhead. But in soccer,
because of transfer values, they are, and also a capital asset,' says John
Camkin, once a director of Coventry City. 'Until, that is, you stop paying
them, whereupon they become valueless to the club because they can go where
they please without earning a transfer fee for you.'
Clubs are not run by idiots - even if it sometimes seems that way. Most have
attempted to create income that doesn't rely solely on match results.
Manchester United now earn more from merchandising than from playing soccer.
Even Leicester have sold an incredible 25,000 copies of their new team shirt
at Pounds 35 a go.
'You daren't rely on what happens on the pitch every Saturday afternoon.
You're running a business, not just a soccer game,' says Steve Kind.
It may be felt that relegation and the subsequent struggle for upward
redemption are part of soccer's appeal to the lifelong fan. After all, there
is hardly a club that hasn't fallen from grace and had to struggle long and
hard to regain its rightful status. Teams built from effort and reward have
always been more popular with British supporters than the side full of
bought-in stars.
However, what seems to be emerging now is the real possibility that the
Premiership and Division One, although notional neighbours, will have the
same relationship as Savoy Hotel guests to the vagrant sleeping rough in the
kitchen doorway - occupying the same patch but hardly interchangeable.
'It will become more difficult for a non-Premier club, trading on its own
resources, to find the players to take it up - or back up - to the top
level,' predicts Steve Coppell, chairman of the LMA. 'There won't be any
more Wimbledons. It isn't going to happen.'
This fact hasn't been lost on the Division One clubs themselves. Although
two will be promoted next May, it will be a hollow victory if their
standards and finances are so below par that they become immediate
casualties after one season in the Premier League.
All season there has been a swirl of rumour that Division One is about to
break away from the Football League and ally itself with the elite as 'Son
of Premier League'.
Privately, the Premier League admits the pressure from below, but says it is
doing nothing to foment revolution. 'The bigger Division One clubs need
crowds, glamour and excitement, and they want out of the League as soon as
possible,' says Camkin of the LMA.
The other crucial change in the footballing scene has been the arrival of
multi-millionaire 'owners' on the model of US sport - men like Jack Walker
at Blackburn, Peter Johnson at Everton, Sir John Hall at Newcastle and Jack
Hayward at Wolves. Their near-limitless willingness to spend is able to
create a business large enough to operate in the big time of the
Premiership.
'Small-town clubs with big ambitions don't want to be out scouting for new
strikers. They should be looking for a billionaire,' says Coppell. 'In the
future, no one is going to take an ordinary run-of-the-mill football club to
the very top level without massive independent financial worth.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
