<HEADLINE>
FT  21 NOV 94 / This Week: Film/Video
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Travel sickness pills are required this week; and a new set of culture-shock
absorbers in your brain. You will be journeying across the known globe.
Your best bet would be to start in Japan with The Seven Samurai (Kurosawa's
classic swashbuckler revived); take a ferry to Hong Kong for the praised
youth film cum portrait of an era (1960s), Days Of Being Wild; cut across
the Indian Ocean to catch Sean Connery in A Good Man In Africa (from William
Boyd's colonialism-satirising novel); nip up to the Mediterranean for the
Italian comedy Dear Diary, an enchanter from film-maker/comedian Nanni
Moretti; then make a wide loop to Cuba via claymore-swishing Scotland
(Highlander III).
                        *      *      *
Cuba, if you arrive there in one piece, has the real oddity of the week.
Strawberries And Chocolate is a gay comedy that, after getting past Castro,
has spent most of the year winning festival prizes. Two young men - one gay,
one straight (is he a watchman for the regime?) - meet, make friends and
move about amid the bizarre subculture of crumbling Havana. Sly satire,
hints of farce - and a brave assault on dogma and bigotry.
                        *      *      *
If you have children you may prefer something more innocent like The
Nightmare Before Christmas. Tim Batman Burton wrote the original story for
this off-the-map puppet phantasmagoria set in Halloweentown. Henry Selick
directed, stuffing our eyes with the richest assemblage of bric-a-brac since
the last scene of Citizen Kane.
Other ghostly influences abound. The film is part Spitting Image, part
Muppet Show, part Svankmajer's Alice. Mostly, though, it is itself: a
gloriously endearing chunk of Toytown Gothic in rich paintbox colours.
                        *      *      *
The video market is bearish this week, growling out little except a poor
children's film (Josh And SAM) and a shlockumentary for adults: OJ Simpson,
The Rise And Fall. Enough already - many of us cry - with the murder-accused
American ex-footballer. But this saga will obviously run and run, at least
until Oliver Stone makes a film of it.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    CUZ  Cuba, Caribbean.
    JPZ  Japan, Asia.
    HKZ  Hong Kong, Asia.
    ITZ  Italy, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
