<HEADLINE>
FT  21 NOV 94 / Labour attacks ministers over spending on wine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour yesterday accused ministers of having an 'obscene sense of
priorities' after disclosing that the government had spent more than Pounds
570,000 on wine for official gatherings in the past five years at an average
of Pounds 5.26 a bottle.
Mr Alan Milburn, a Labour MP, said the purchasing was done by a quango
called the Government Hospitality Fund Advisory Committee for the Purchase
of Wine, under the auspices of the Foreign Office. The quango, headed by Sir
Ewen Fergusson, a former Ambassador to France, cost Pounds 1,500 a year to
run.
Mr Milburn accused the committee of wasteful expenditure at a time when Mr
Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, was calling for public expenditure
restraint. He said: 'With huge spending cuts being planned, it is an obscene
sense of priorities to lavish large sums of public money on buying wine to
dish out at receptions.'
Mr Milburn said the money spent on wine could have bought 500 cataract
extractions or 100 coronary artery by-pass operations.
The Foreign Office said the average spending of Pounds 110,000 a year 'does
not necessarily mean that money was actually used in the last year, because
some wine is bought and then stored'. It said there were 500 functions last
year across government departments.
Such entertainment, involving people from all walks of life, was in 'direct
support of government activities and objectives', it said, citing diverse
examples such as the promotion of exports and an achievement award ceremony
for disabled people.
Nor were members involved in decisions on purchasing, which was the
responsibility of officials of the fund.
</TEXT>
