<HEADLINE>
FT  21 NOV 94 / Tories 'need killer facts' to stop electoral death:
Backbench 'yobbos' urged to hit back at Blair - Warning given that small
businesses feel let down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'Killer facts' are what the Conservative party needs if it is to win the
next general election, according to a strategy paper produced by Mr John
Maples, the party's deputy chairman and a former Treasury minister.
The facts are soundbites, such as: 'Since 1980, the UK economy has grown
faster than Germany and the gap is widening.' They need to be trumpeted 'ad
nauseam' because, as the market research appendix to the paper shows, a core
element of the Conservative party's support, those on average incomes,
perceive the government as 'ineffectual and unable to deliver its promises'.
Written on September 30 and based on extensive research among people who
'voted Conservative in April 1992 but now say they might or would not', the
paper shows the large extent of the challenge faced by the party to reverse
Labour's lead in the opinion polls and plots a possible communications
strategy.
It throws light on the usually obscured relationship between party machinery
and government departments. As the introduction to the paper says: 'If the
ideas set out are accepted by ministers then detailed programmes will need
to be developed with relevant departments.'
Because the paper was intended to be read only by Mr John Major and a
restricted circle in Conservative Central Office and Downing Street, its
language and tone are rather more frank and perhaps cynical than the normal
ministerial soundbite.
To give one example, Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, would
probably not wish to be caught saying: 'The best result for the next 12
months would be zero media coverage of the National Health Service.'
However, that is Mr Maples's conclusion to a long analysis of what the party
should do to reduce Labour's opinion poll lead over the Tories on which of
the parties would manage the health service better.
Nor would Mrs Bottomley opine publicly that 'we can never win on this
issue', as does Mr Maples. His paper says Labour's lead on this issue is 55
per cent and that a realistic target would be to reduce this margin to 30
per cent by October 1995.
The basis of the paper is a qualitative research programme - market research
which attempts to give a more detailed account of how individuals think and
feel than mainstream quantitative opinion polls.
The target of the research was two groups of Conservative voters: those in
the middle-income, white-collar 'BC1' category and those in the 'C2' top end
of the blue-collar group. Both have been a vital element in the party's last
three general election victories. The purpose was to 'explore in depth why
their support had slipped'.
Opinions were solicited from eight groups of eight people, with equal
numbers of men and women in each, divided between BC1s and C2s. The
discussions were held in Oldham, Birmingham, London and Brighton and
participants fell into one of two age groups: 25 to 40-year-olds and 40 to
60-year-olds. There were also two pensioners' groups.
There is a widespread conviction among senior Conservatives that the party
must keep the votes of individuals in these categories if it is to win the
next general election. At first glance, therefore, the results make grim
reading for the party.
Mr Maples provides points of the 'general picture' emerging from the
interviews. As the views of Conservative voters, they are slightly
surprising:
'There is a feeling of powerlessness and insecurity about jobs, housing,
health service, business, family value, crime etc and no vision of where we
are heading.'
'Although in the 1980s the Conservatives seemed to promise a classless
society of opportunity, the reality is now that the rich are getting richer
on the backs of the rest, who are getting poorer.'
'Privatisation has not been popular and small businessmen in particular feel
'let down'.'
'Very few people think we are out of recession.'
'The Conservatives have let voters down: they have been in government too
long, are complacent and have lost a sense of direction. They fail to fulfil
promises, are clumsy at implementing policy and 'shoot themselves in the
foot'.'
However, many of these individuals' other views - 'very rightwing views on
crime and immigration, deep disapproval of 'scrounging' on social security .
. . deep fear of 'loony lefties', distrust of politically-correct,
liberal-minded 'do-gooders'' - make them 'natural Conservatives'.
The market research identifies 'failure of communication' as at the heart of
the disenchantment. 'What we are saying is at odds with their experience,
which leads them to conclude that we are 'out of touch', 'lying', 'don't
care', 'think they are stupid',' it says.
That is why Mr Maples believes a detailed communications plan is important.
The period between now and the election, which 'could be as little as 20
months away and no more than 30 months' is divided into four phases in the
fledgling communications plan - up to the 1995 party conference; from then
to the start of a short pre-election campaign; a third phase, the
pre-election campaign, four to six months before polling day; and the
election campaign.
The 'phase one' proposal is to overtake or reduce the Labour party's opinion
poll lead in four crucial policy areas for these average income supporters,
as identified by the research. 'We should . . . by the 1995 conference . . .
seek to re-establish polling leads on the economy and law and order while
reducing our deficits on education and health.'
The messages should be positive in this initial phase. In stage two, the
party will 'need to scare the voters about Labour and the Liberals'.
The process of getting the message across has several strands, ranging from
party political use of the parliamentary timetable to a more ruthless
approach to relationships with press and television.
On the latter Mr Maples says:
'We should not just concentrate on political and specialist correspondents
but on columnists, leader writers and editors.'
'We need to set and control the agenda as much as we can and be much less
'reactive'.'
'We need to feed our friends and potential friends in the press with good
stories.' 'For television and radio, we should use good performers
ruthlessly.'
'The ability to react rapidly to events and Labour allegations is vital.
They are much better than us at this.'
'A programme of 'marking' and building relationships with proprietors,
editors, correspondents etc needs planning and implementation.'
A section on the style of a media campaign suggests Mr Maples may not have
learned one lesson of the research, which is not to patronise these middle
and lower income groups: 'While ABC1s can conceptualise, C2s and Ds often
cannot. They can relate only to things they can see and feel. They absorb
their information and often views from television and tabloids. We have to
talk to them in a way they understand.'
However effective any campaign to bring round the media may turn out to be,
the party also needs to regain control of the political agenda.
Mr Maples urges that the parliamentary timetable is managed far better so
that popular measures, relevant debates and ministerial statements receive
public attention, and are not crowded out by news of uncontrolled events.
One technique for propagating good news is to identify a series of 'killer
facts'. The paper says: 'We need to develop say five facts in each key area
which are positive and which we repeat endlessly eg 'One million more
patients treated annually since NHS reforms'.'
A series of policy changes are suggested to defuse the main criticisms of
disenchanted supporters. These include slowing the pace of NHS reform,
postponing the second instalment of value added tax on fuel and reform of
the system of taxing executive share options to deter some of the excesses
of executive pay packages.
Another important strand in the campaign is to solicit 'endorsements' from
'friends' such as the police and the Confederation of British Industry.
The main objective, underlying all strands of the communications strategy,
is to make sure that what the party says corresponds to supporters' real
experiences. Mr Maples identifies the economy as an important area of
weakness. He points out: 'While we trumpet the recovery, the voters do not
think the recession has ended. They still fear unemployment, have no more
'money in their pocket' etc. What we are saying is completely at odds with
their experience.'
The reason for this mismatch is that, because of tax increases, real
take-home pay is falling this year and 'will fall again in 1995 to 1996. We
have to see this rise soon or we will have had four or even five years of
recovery with no rise in living standards'.
The problem of matching ministerial claims to reality is less acute in law
and order.
Mr Maples says: 'We cannot be tough enough for our audience (on law and
order) but they do not know what we are doing and all the real evidence says
to them that crime is worse.'
One solution is to 'stop or at least criticise those responsible for light
sentences, safari trips, prosecution of people 'who have a go' at criminals,
early release from prison etc'.
Reversing Labour's 39 per cent poll lead on education issues will be
tougher. The market research survey showed that 'talk of competition,
budgets, management etc triggers negative perceptions of treating education
like a business'.
However, it continues: 'It does not matter that much of the education
establishment is hostile - they are rightly seen as part of the problem.'
The gravest problem of all for the government is perception of NHS reforms:
'People perceive the reforms as clumsy and believe what doctors and nurses
say about them, which is almost universally hostile.'
Apart from a total media blackout of NHS coverage, the next best strategy is
to identify a few 'killer facts' for 'endless repetition'. But these should
be more than national statistics: 'Could we have a number per month (of
patients treated) for a typical hospital, or even for particular local
hospitals.'
It would also help to dam the flow of bad news. 'We must think about what we
can do to stop the staff being so critical to patients.'
The paper devotes little attention to two traditional battleground areas -
the unions and Europe. Of the unions, the paper says: 'This issue is low on
people's priority lists.' The market research says: 'These (unions are no
longer seen as a threat, indeed people feel that employees now have little
or no protection against employers and need more.'
Europe, too, is said to be 'very low on their list of concerns'. The
ingredients for campaigning success are a united party and 'that we remain
more Eurosceptic than Labour'.
Apart from these individual issues, the paper urges a coherent strategy for
dealing with the Labour party. The research shows that 'apart from the NHS,
Blair is the only thing they really have going for them'.
He says of the Labour party leader: 'If Blair turns out to be as good as he
looks we have a problem.' The traditional method of attacking a Labour
leader is redundant because the Conservatives 'cannot paint Blair as a left
winger'.
They should, however, be 'constantly throwing his past views at him and
trying to create and exploit the huge gap between Blair and most of his
party'.
Mr Maples has a suggestion: 'Could we set some backbenchers on to this?
Maybe a few yobbos of our own to try to knock him about a bit and another
team to operate more subtly on the changes of mind and differences of view.'
He says the government should introduce legislation likely to split Mr Blair
from the rest of his party. 'A proposal on ID cards and/or further
industrial relations legislation (eg to reballot on public service strikes)
would force them to take a view. Either Blair will support our proposals and
divide his party, or oppose us and show he does not really mean what he says
about strikes and crime,' he says.
Mr Maples sums up the campaign in a section headed 'listen'. He says that
too often the party appears not to be listening to its supporters and is too
didactic. Instead he recommends: 'Listening, explaining, being honest and
open, inviting feedback and dialogue.'
</TEXT>
