<HEADLINE>
FT  21 NOV 94 / Appraisal by staff urged for chiefs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Part of the pay of chief executives should be determined by employee
appraisal, the MSF technical union says in a report today.
It suggests that chief executives who expect employees to have part of their
pay related to performance should put their own performance and pay to the
same sort of test.
A survey of MSF representatives in 472 organisations found that
three-quarters wanted to be involved in the appraisal of their managers.
The survey found that before the introduction of techniques such as human
resource management and total quality management, 88 per cent of
representatives were ambivalent to them. After they were introduced the
proportion opposed to them doubled to 24 per cent.
The report says that while new techniques such as empowerment promised
greater employee control, only a tenth of those questioned thought this had
actually happened.
New Management: An MSF Guide. MSF, 64-66 Wandsworth Common Northside, London
SW18 2SH. Pounds 10, free to members.
</TEXT>
