<HEADLINE>
FT  21 NOV 94 / Hotel pay 'rises 3% or more'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Employment Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Many of Britain's biggest hotel chains and catering companies have raised
the wages of their low-paid workers by 3 per cent or more since the
government's abolition of the wages councils last year, says a study
published today.
The findings by Incomes Data Services appear to contradict fears that the
end of statutory protection for the low paid would encourage employers to
drive down wages in weakly organised sectors such as hotels and catering.
Mr Chris Pond, head of the independent Low Pay Unit, said yesterday that it
showed big companies were 'using their market power to gain a competitive
edge by attracting the best staff available'.
The report found minimum pay rates covering more than 10,000 employees in
hotels had been raised by at least the rate of inflation to Pounds 3.07 an
hour, maintaining in real terms the minimum set down by the wages council
for the industry before its demise last year.
The report says that many companies in catering have frozen minimum rates or
introduced new lower starting rates for staff, using the cost savings made
to provide higher rises for more experienced staff.
A report published today by the National Association of Citizens Advice
Bureaux says pay and conditions of employment have deteriorated in recent
months for a growing number of people working in London.
The report, based on evidence of employment problems from 48 local bureaux
in the capital, shows that the abolition of the wages councils and erosion
of employment protection have driven down wages in many small companies.
The report found that wages have fallen as low as Pounds 1 an hour for some
catering jobs. It says employers are replacing permanent staff with workers
on short-term contracts to prevent them reaching the two-year qualifying
threshold for employment protection.
The report says employers in London are withdrawing holiday and sick pay,
imposing commission-only work and breaching health and safety regulations.
'With no protection against unfair dismissal, many workers are faced with a
choice between accepting less pay and longer hours or the sack,' it says.
The report calls for a reduction in the two-year qualifying period for
protection against unfair dismissal to at least its pre-1979 level of six
months.
Report No 677. Incomes Data Services, 193 St John Street, London.
In Work and Out of Pocket, CAB Occasional Paper No 5. Social Policy and
Service Development Unit, NACAB London division, 136-144 City Road, London
ECIV 2QN.
</TEXT>
