<HEADLINE>
FT  21 NOV 94 / Smooth operator balked at the polls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As a specialist communicator and a senior Conservative Central Office
official, it is clear why Mr John Maples was handed the responsibility of
finding ways for the government to turn back the tide of negative publicity,
William Lewis writes.
Following his defeat at the 1992 general election at Lewisham West in
London, where he had been MP since 1983, he was appointed chairman and chief
executive of Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Government Communications Worldwide, the
advertising agency's government lobbying offshoot. The subsidiary was set up
after the election to 'deal with communications between governments and
their people and people and their governments'.
Mr Maples's move to Saatchi apparently came about after he impressed senior
executives at the company. In the approach to the election Mr Maples, then
economic secretary to the Treasury, emerged as one of the government's most
effective television communicators. His performances, routinely described as
smooth, made him one of the rising stars. He was tipped for immediate
promotion to the cabinet after the election.
Even after his defeat many in the party felt sure that it would not be long
before Mr Maples returned.
The path back has not been a wholly smooth one. He is said to have applied
to become the Conservative candidate for the Newbury by-election earlier
this year, but was rejected. This was widely blamed on support for his
candidacy from Central Office, against which there was some animosity in the
local party organisation. It remains to be seen whether he will find a safe
seat before the next general election.
</TEXT>
