<HEADLINE>
FT  21 NOV 94 / Budget 1994: Mawhinney may turn transport in a new direction
 -Charles Batchelor says the government will be able to show at little cost
whether it favours public systems over the car
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government will have an opportunity to spell out its commitment to
public transport at very little cost in the Budget on November 29. Mr Brian
Mawhinney, transport secretary for the past four months, will be able to
demonstrate whether his sympathies lie with public transport or the car and
respond to growing pressure to switch spending.
At the same time government plans to involve private finance in the public
transport infrastructure mean it would not be required to pledge large
amounts of public finance to any ventures.
The Department of Transport set out its stall earlier this month in a glossy
catalogue, Building Tomorrow's Transport Network, which lists infrastructure
projects in which private finance will play an important role.
Among the opportunities identified are several projects for which
preparations are well advanced, such as the Pounds 500m West Coast rail line
modernisation, and 'design, build, finance and operate' road schemes. They
include Crossrail, the underground rail link across London which is looking
for an alternative way forward after being rejected by a parliamentary
committee.
A few days after the publication of this catalogue Sir Alastair Morton,
chairman of the panel set up to promote projects eligible for private funds,
said his main problem had shifted from finding suitable projects to handling
the work coming in.
Sir Alastair said the private finance initiative had the backing of Mr John
Major, the prime minister, and its potential was now more clearly recognised
in government departments. The panel has identified projects worth Pounds
10bn, some in transport but others in fields such as information technology,
water and sewage and education.
Among the projects the chancellor might seek to highlight in his Budget
statement are:
Light rail or 'supertram' projects planned in several cities. A strong case
for public backing can be made by the Croydon Tramlink, a 17-mile network to
improve communications in south London. It would provide an orbital link
between Wimbledon, Croydon, Beckenham and New Addington, reducing bus
journey times on crowded suburban roads.
Its promoters, London Transport and Croydon Borough, believe that because
London travellers are used to paying higher fares, the private sector would
be willing to provide more than half the Pounds 160m cost of the scheme.
This would be far more than raised for earlier tram projects in Manchester
and Sheffield.
A second tram project which is well advanced is the Midland Metro, which
would link central Birmingham with Wolverhampton over 13 miles of track. The
private sector contribution to this Pounds 112m scheme is estimated at just
Pounds 10m but it would make a considerable contribution to reducing
congestion.
New rolling stock for London Underground's Northern Line. London Underground
fought to have this project accepted under the private finance initiative
and has two remaining bidders for the Pounds 400m project. The chancellor
may announce final approval in the Budget.
Thameslink 2000, which would quadruple capacity on London's only cross-town
rail link, between London Bridge and St Pancras stations. The government has
said this Pounds 500m project must be financed entirely by the private
sector. It would extend the cross-London link to new destinations in East
Anglia and on the south coast.
The West Coast line featured in last year's Budget announcement and a
project team is trying to define the scheme more closely so that it can be
put out to tender next year.
The revival of interest in rail following the completion of the Channel
tunnel has attracted the attention of consultant engineers and construction
companies. The roads programme is being cut. Even so, road-related schemes
could still feature in the Budget. They could include:
Proposals for a second Forth road bridge costing an estimated Pounds 400m
which are being studied by the Scottish Office. On present estimates the
existing road bridge, dating from 1964, will soon be heavily congested. The
Lothian region would prefer improvements to rail services. Technologies for
the introduction of electronic tolls on motorways are being evaluated by the
Department of Transport for testing next year. The chancellor may announce
more details of the expected private sector contribution. A second tranche
of 'design, build, finance and operate' projects, paid for by the government
through 'shadow' tolls, may be announced following the unveiling of the
first four projects last August.
The chancellor may, however, surprise his listeners with schemes which have
received no previous publicity.
Channel tunnel, Page 13
Letters, Page 18
</TEXT>
