<HEADLINE>
FT  21 NOV 94 / Blunkett backs school exam tables
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David Blunkett, the shadow education secretary, yesterday risked
provoking a clash between Labour and the main teaching unions by saying that
his party would continue to implement school league tables if elected to
power.
As the government prepared to publish the third annual set of school league
tables tomorrow Mr Blunkett said Labour would seek to improve the system of
categorising schools' performance, increasing the range of information that
the tables contain.
Amid indications that Labour is willing to back some aspects of the
government's education reforms he made clear that his party would modify the
tables to add better measures of effectiveness.
He told BBC Television: 'I am in favour of information and I don't think you
can hide that information from parents.' He said the publication of the
tables must 'mean something in terms of rewarding, backing, supporting
schools that are really doing a first-rate job'.
His comments were greeted as an 'enormous U-turn' in Labour policy by Mrs
Gillian Shephard, the education secretary. She said the opposition party had
finally 'seen sense' on the issue.
Mr Blunkett continued to take a particularly hostile stance towards tax
perks for independent schools, in spite of recent indications that Labour
politicians were seeking a less confrontational approach on the issue.
In particular, he said his party would abolish tax relief and charitable
status for non-state schools.
The NASUWT teachers' union said yesterday that the league tables were
divisive and too often 'simply a device with which to whip teachers'.
Offering different sorts of league tables was 'simply asking teachers which
sort of whip they would like to be beaten with'.
The NUT, the biggest teachers' union, was more cautious, simply stressing
its opposition to tables in their present form.
Mrs Shephard reiterated that she would no longer be working towards setting
targets for the number of schools opting out of local authority control.
She said that she would be working towards creating 'a great number' but
added 'I'm not working to targets.'
The table makers, Page 18
