<HEADLINE>
FT  21 NOV 94 / Signing of peace accord fails to allay Angola fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN and NICHOLAS SHAXSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUSAKA, LUANDA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Prospects for peace in Angola remained uncertain last night despite the
signing of an agreement to end the country's 19-year civil war which has
cost half a million lives.
A warm handshake between Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos and General
Eugenio Manuvakola, who signed on behalf of the Unita rebel movement, did
little to allay fears aroused by the absence from the ceremony of its
leader, Mr Jonas Savimbi.
The agreement, in which the warring parties pledge a ceasefire with effect
from midnight tomorrow, envisages the integration of Unita forces into the
army, a coalition government and fresh national elections, which will be
monitored by a 7,000-strong United Nations force.
Although the UN will be relieved that the signing took place, the occasion
fell well short of what had been planned. President dos Santos delegated the
signing of the document to his foreign minister and the government
delegation outnumbered the three-member Unita team led by Gen Manuvakola,
Unita's secretary general and chief negotiator.
The official programme for the ceremony, held in Lusaka's Mulungushi
conference hall and attended by African leaders and senior western
officials, listed Mr Savimbi as one of the participants. But over the
weekend Unita officials said that an Angolan government military offensive
launched a fortnight ago would prevent Mr Savimbi from attending.
Although Gen Manuvakola said yesterday that Unita intended to implement the
deal, Mr Savimbi has yet to make his position clear. A 1991 peace agreement,
negotiated by US and Soviet Union diplomats, collapsed after Mr Savimbi
refused to accept defeat by President dos Santos' MPLA party in the
following year's election.
The renewed conflict has left Angola even more bitterly divided but the
recent MPLA offensive may have left the government with the upper hand, with
some generals said to be calling for a further push.
Government forces recently captured the Unita stronghold of Huambo, 530km
south-east of the capital, Luanda. The offensive forced the postponement of
the signing, originally due to take place last Tuesday, and may yet imperil
the agreement. Privately some western diplomats wonder whether they should
have been more forceful in urging restraint on Luanda, but are letting
Africa take the initiative.
Southern African leaders who attended the signing are understood to have
warned Mr Savimbi that they are prepared to offer military assistance to the
MPLA government if they decide he is to blame should the peace process
collapse a second time.
Nicholas Shaxson adds from Luanda: Both sides in Angola have access to
substantial funds should war resume. The government is pumping around
Dollars 2.5bn (Pounds 1.5bn) a year of offshore oil. Unita still controls
much of the north-eastern diamond trade, last year worth some Dollars 250m,
despite substantial advances by government forces this year. Mr Savimbi has
an old ally in President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire, Angola's northern
neighbour.
Recent US Republican electoral victories will revive the influence of Unita
friends, such as Senator Jesse Helms, incoming chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, who formerly encouraged military support for Mr
Savimbi.
The government has ceded to Unita three second-rate provincial governorships
as well as four minor ministries. But key governorships including Luanda,
Huambo, Benguela and diamond-rich Lunda Norte, as well as the ministries of
defence, interior, economy and petroleum, will remain in MPLA hands.
</TEXT>
