<HEADLINE>
FT  21 NOV 94 / Rio slums crackdown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil's armed forces sealed off seven of Rio de Janeiro's shanty towns over
the weekend in a move one military commander described as 'psychological
intimidation' of the city's drug traffickers, Angus Foster writes from Sao
Paulo.
The exercises, which involved more than 1,000 troops and police, were the
biggest since the federal government last month gave the military control
over rounding up Rio's drug kings. The city's police force, widely corrupted
by drug money, had lost control of Rio's several hundred shanty towns to the
traffickers.
The armed forces' movements encountered almost no resistance and were
largely welcomed by residents.
The government decided to use troops partly because of a massacre of 13
shanty town residents by police last month.
</TEXT>
