<HEADLINE>
FT  21 NOV 94 / Tory chief sets out wish-list to boost party image
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A blackout on media coverage of the National Health Service and a plan to
have back-bench 'yobbos' metaphorically beat up the Labour leader, Mr Tony
Blair, feature in the wish-list of a draft Conservative party communications
plan for the run-up to the next election.
Not intended for publication, it was written by Mr John Maples, the party's
deputy chairman, for Mr John Major, the prime minister, and Conservative
central office.
It is based on detailed interviews with 80 people who voted Tory in the 1992
election but who now say they might not or would not, because they see the
government as 'ineffectual and unable to deliver its promises'.
Those surveyed were in the so-called 'BC1' and 'C2' average income social
categories, whose support was crucial to the Conservatives' three previous
election victories. They are described in the research as 'natural
Conservatives', but they disapprove of privatisation and believe that the
'rich are getting richer on the backs of the rest'. Mr Maples' proposal for
wooing them back, dated September 30 1994, says the election 'could be as
little as 20 months away and no more than 30 months'. It identifies the task
before the 1995 Conservative party conference as eroding or reversing the
Labour party's lead in the opinion polls on four issues: the economy, law
and order, education and the National Health Service. On the economy, Mr
Maples says: 'The crucial issue here is living standards', which are
'falling in 1994 to 1995' and will fall 'again in 1995 to 1996'. He says the
government's talk of recovery is 'completely at odds with their (the
surveyed Tory supporters') experience'.
He believes that Labour's lead on law and order can be reversed, but is
pessimistic on the NHS, where Labour has a 55 percentage point lead over the
Tories.
'We can never win on this issue,' the paper says. 'The best result for the
next 12 months would be zero media coverage of the National Health Service.'
Labour's other great electoral asset is identified as its leader, Mr Tony
Blair. The paper says: 'If Blair turns out to be as good as he looks, we
have a problem.'
It continues: 'We cannot paint Blair as a left winger.' However, it urges a
strategy of drawing commitments from the Labour leader which illustrate the
divide between him and many members of his party. 'Could we set some back
benchers on to this?' the paper asks. 'Maybe a few yobbos of our own to try
to knock him about a bit.' The market research shows statements by Mr John
Prescott, Labour's deputy leader, on returning to full employment are
'striking a chord'. The paper asks: 'Can we go any way down this path? . . .
It would help neutralise any possible Labour advantage.'
Legislation designed to split Mr Blair from the rest of his party - such as
on ID cards - is proposed. Mr Maples also suggests delaying the pace of NHS
reform, postponing the imposition of the second instalment of VAT on fuel
and increasing the tax levied on executive share options.
Mr Tim Collins, Tory communications director, last night said that though Mr
Maples was formulating the communications plan, he had no policy-making
role.
Tories 'need killer facts' to stop electoral death, Page 10
</TEXT>
