<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Serious Money): A prodigal returns to the
fold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN O'CONNOR, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Share buy-backs are one of those rarities: a financial fashion that is also
a thoroughly sensible idea. The regional electricity companies have been
buying back their own shares in dribs and drabs for some time. This week,
Boots and National Power joined the club.
The general argument in favour of buy-backs is being muddied by specific
discussion of the best way of doing them. A buy-back is just what it sounds
like: a company uses its own spare cash to buy some of its own shares, just
as it might use the money to buy shares in another company when plotting a
take-over.
Investment pundits such as Warren Buffett, the US guru, favour share
buy-backs as strongly as they condemn hubristic bids. Expensive take-overs
hurt shareholder value twice over. First, a bad acquisition damages the
actual business of the predator. Then, it damages the share rating as
investors see that loss of value and lose confidence in the management.
By contrast, if a company buys back its own shares, it creates a virtuous
circle. Provided the price is right, the move reduces the number of ordinary
shares more sharply than the offsetting fall in investment income reduces
earnings. So, earnings per share rise. An expensive bid often has the
opposite effect: earnings per share fall.
Thus, basic arithmetic suggests that a sensible buy-back is a better way of
spending shareholders' money than expensive acquisitions. Shareholders'
perception of this basic arithmetic prompts them to increase their estimates
of the company's earnings power and the ability of its managers - and so the
share price rises even further.
It is particularly heart-warming to see Boots in the buy-back club. Welcome
to a very prodigal son.
Here is the parable in brief. In 1989, Boots won a fiercely contested Pounds
900m bid for Ward White despite fierce opposition from some of its own
shareholders. Once recession bit, the only question was quite how badly
Boots had overpaid.
Now, Boots is selling its drugs business to a German company and has spent
Pounds 500m buying back its own shares. The only worry is that the
additional Pounds 350m Boots is due to get for the drugs business will soon
be burning a hole in its pocket.
MONDAY WAS A red-letter day for gambling buffs. The national lottery opened
its doors and BSkyB published its pathfinder prospectus.
Buying shares in a satellite television company which has yet to make any
worth-while profits is essentially speculative. Applying for BSkyB shares is
not quite such a leap in the dark as subscribing to the Eurotunnel launch or
a new biotech company, but it has very little in common with investing in
Marks and Spencer.
To label it speculative is not necessarily to criticise. As the stampede for
lottery tickets showed, many Brits love a good speculation. What is
important is clear labelling.
BSkyB (in which Pearson, owner of the FT, has a 17.5 per cent stake) is
setting out to woo the personal investor. And the shares will be sold
through share shops - Sid's old stamping ground.
But when the government sold off the riskier privatisations, such as British
Airways, it deliberately steered clear of Sids on the ground that the shares
were not suitable for inexperienced investors.
BSkyB can hardly afford to take such high moral ground. The satellite
company has an obvious interest in having customers who double as
shareholders.
One of the biggest worries of television companions such as TeleWest and
BSkyB is their 'churn rate' - lapsed subscribers. Customers who have a
vested interest in the company's success may well prove more loyal in both
their capacities.
What is needed is a strong wealth warning: 'These shares are likely to be
riskier than many others.' After all, it is unlikely to deter the punters.
IT SOUNDS AN unbeatable offer from Bank of Scotland: a five-year bank
deposit paying 5 per cent gross a year plus a bonus 'equivalent to the
average percentage rise in the FT-SE 100 index' between December 1 1994 and
December 1 1999.
Yes, but what exactly does the bank mean by 'average percentage rise' ? What
it does not mean is the actual rise over that period.
For the small print explains that the bank's stock market index deposit
calculates the 'average' by taking each of the 20 three-month periods
between the start and finish dates, working out a rise between December 1
1994 and the end of each period - and then averaging.
The bank's own example shows an actual stock market rise of more than 30 per
cent translated into a bonus of only 15 per cent. And both income and bonus
are subject to income tax. Tricky things, words.
</TEXT>
<XX>
