<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / Weekend Money: Finance Week
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS
Ireland was pitched into political crisis after the prime minister, Albert
Reynolds, and his Fianna Fail cabinet colleagues resigned.
Camelot, the operator of the UK's first national lottery for more than 150
years, said it was 'absolutely delighted' with early sales of tickets.
Ready-made meals comprised almost 35 per cent of the average household's
food bill last year, a rise of nearly 10 per cent since the early 1980s,
according to the 1993 National Food Survey.
The Post Office is close to a deal with a leading insurer that would enable
it to sell travel insurance through many of its 20,000 branches.
Better than expected figures for UK inflation, unemployment and the public
finances provided chancellor Kenneth Clarke with a strong base for a
confidence-building Budget.
Independent gas companies hoping to enter the lucrative market for supplying
Britain's 18m households were relieved to learn from the Queen's speech that
legislation for removing British Gas's monopoly will be introduced soon.
About 7m people who have mortgages with building societies would be given
new rights to vote on issues affecting societies if proposals put forward by
the sector's trade body are accepted by the government.
MARKETS
In one of the most frenetic days ever on the London Metal Exchange, prices
soared on Wednesday as wave after wave of investment fund and speculative
buying took copper, aluminium and lead to fresh four-year peaks and nickel
and zinc to their highest levels for two years.
Many large pension funds are close to including commodities in their
investment portfolios as a way of diversifying away from traditional
financial holdings, according to Steven Strongin, vice-president and
commodities strategist at Goldman Sachs, the US investment bank.
The US Federal Reserve surprised the financial markets with an increase of
three-quarters of a percentage point in short-term interest rates intended
to keep inflation under control.
Plans to launch a pan-European stock market for fast-growing companies were
unveiled by a group of European venture capitalists, the Paris Bourse and
the US Nasdaq market.
Lazard Investors is to launch an Indian equity fund next week in conjunction
with BK Birla, the Indian business group, and the Bombay-based merchant bank
Creditcapital Finance Corporation, in which Lazard Investors holds 40 per
cent.
Rising interest rates are encouraging more gold mining companies to hedge
their future production, and this appears to be putting a 'cap' on any price
rise above Dollars 400 a troy ounce, according to the World Gold Council.
COMPANIES
British Aerospace has increased its bid for VSEL. The latest offer is a 3.3
for one share swap, worth around Pounds 14.70 for each VSEL share, with a
Pounds 14 cash alternative matching GEC's Pounds 14 cash offer.
Shares in cash-rich De La Rue, the bank-note printer, hit an all-time high
as the market responded to a sparkling set of interim results.
Land Securities, the UK's largest quoted property group, tumbled 17p to 606p
on Wednesday on turnover of 7.5m shares - the busiest session for 18 months
 -after a warning about the second half.
The third-quarter figures season for the insurance composites ended with a
whimper of disappointment as General Accident's results included shock paper
losses from its market investments, particularly in the US.
Sam Chisholm, the chief executive of British Sky Broadcasting, could receive
up to Pounds 3m this year in salary and bonuses, the pathfinder prospectus
for the satellite television venture revealed.
British Sky Broadcasting believes it lost around 50,000 existing and
potential new customers through pirate devices.
GWR, the expanding Bristol-based commercial radio group, has had its radio
licences acquisition plan blocked by the Radio Authority, even though a
similar scheme involving Emap and Trans World Communications was accepted.
Attwoods described the increased bid of Pounds 391m from Browning-Ferris
Industries of the US as meagre and cynical, and urged shareholders to reject
the offer in favour of the proposed break-up plan.
British Steel, Europe's second largest steel-maker, is raising its interim
dividend from 0.5p a share to 2p after a surge in half-year pre-tax profits
from Pounds 27m to Pounds 159m.
Automotive Financial Group Holdings, one of the biggest UK motor retailer
groups and controlled by Octav Botnar, has been sold to the Barclay
brothers, the reclusive UK entrepreneurs, in a deal understood to be worth
about Pounds 200m.
Shares in Towry Law, the independent financial advice group, dropped 44p to
86p on Wednesday after the group, which floated last November, warned that
it expected losses of Pounds 1.25m at the half year, compared with pre-tax
profits of Pounds 565,000.
RJB Mining expects to have cleared all debts incurred in its bid for the
English regions of British Coal by the end of 1998, and is looking for
pre-tax profit margins of about 18 per cent in 1999.
Acquisitions following its 1993 rights issue helped Great Portland Estates,
the UK's sixth largest property company, announce interim pre-tax profits
ahead from Pounds 16m to Pounds 21.4m.
Boots is to end 80 years of prescription medicine manufacture with the sale
of its drugs business to BASF of Germany for 'about Pounds 850m'. Boots
later spent Pounds 508m on buying back its shares on the stock market, which
will leave Boots' management free to concentrate on acquisitions in
over-the-counter (non-prescription) drugs, probably in Germany.
Barclays Bank also reduced excess capital by announcing that it would buy
back Dollars 500m (Pounds 300m) of non-cumulative preference shares.
BrightReasons, the owner of Pizzaland, has become the latest new-issues
casualty. The company announced that its share offer would be 'delayed'.
PowerGen is considering joint ventures with other European companies as a
means of honouring a commitment to try to dispose of 2,000MW of plant.
Gartmore is to launch an investment trust to track a new index covering the
smallest 1 per cent of UK equities by market capitalisation.
Foreign &amp; Colonial's offer of C-shares in its Emerging Markets investment
trust was almost fully subscribed, raising Pounds 113.7m, to add to its
existing Pounds 150m of funds. Fidelity's launch of the new Fidelity Special
Values investment trust was less successful, pulling in Pounds 45.4m against
early hopes of up to Pounds 125m. Most of the money came from private
investors through financial advisers.
Microsoft announced plans for a world-wide, on-line information service for
personal computer users.
Carriage House Motors, Manhattan's Rolls-Royce dealership, closes its doors
on East 61st Street next month.
</TEXT>
