<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): A reader writes . . .
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Having just returned from a four-day holiday in Paris, I felt compelled to
write regarding the daylight robbery of holiday-makers by currency shops. My
first transaction - a Pounds 100 traveller's cheque on October 26 via Banque
Indosuez - was at a rate of 8.18 francs to the pound. This resulted in an
exchange of 818 francs, inclusive of commission.
My second transaction the following day was at a Chequepoint Bureau adjacent
to the Pompidou Centre.
When I inquired about the rate, the clerk pointed to a board which displayed
numerous figures and conditions - all, of course, in French, which I do not
speak.
While the rate of FFr8.05 did not appear quite as good as my previous day's
exchange, I was happy to proceed on the basis of expediency. So, I signed my
traveller's cheque for Pounds 200.
The clerk then made a lengthy telephone call which, he said, was necessary
to safeguard my interests against theft. Following this, I was presented
with FFr1,430 and a receipt showing an exchange rate of FFr7.15.
I questioned this but was told it was correct. An argument ensued, during
which I asked for the transaction to be cancelled and demanded my cheque be
returned. I was not successful so I went to Chequepoint's head office in the
Avenue des Champs-Elysees. There, I encountered a very hostile manager.
Incidentally, I checked the bank rate later that day with Banque Indosuez;
it was FFr8.12. The difference of FFr0.97 between the two rates is 11.9 per
cent - which is quite extortionate.
My error, of course, was in not firmly establishing the rate beforehand. But
I cannot imagine why the authorities in France allow such money shops to
operate.
I would be most interested to hear if you have received letters from other
aggrieved travellers. I should also be interested to know if there is any
authority in France to which I can write on this subject.
The French need to bring the activities of these 'money bandits' to heel.
John Gordon-Smith
Oxton,
Birkenhead, Merseyside
</TEXT>
