<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): Profit from renting -
Briefcase, Q&amp;A
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
My wife and I have been renting our houses in England while we have been
living in Germany where I am employed by a German company (my wife does not
work). This year will be the first when we will see a profit from our UK
rental income. The houses are in both our names. Are we each entitled to a
UK personal tax allowance for this year - and, if so, how much is it?
Yes - Pounds 3,445 each, plus a married couple's allowance for you of Pounds
1,720 at 20 per cent (viz, Pounds 344 actual tax relief).
You forgot to tell us if the houses are let furnished (and thus fall within
Schedule D case VI) or unfurnished (Schedule A), and whether the rent is
being paid direct to your joint bank account, for example (and thus having
25 per cent tax withheld by the tenants), or to an agent in the UK (and thus
having no tax deducted).
If it is being paid to an agent, the tax for the present year, 1994-95, is
due for payment on New Year's day. The way in which the New Year's day
liability is calculated (subject to adjustment after April 5 1995) depends
upon whether the profits are assessable under Schedule A or D.
If you are in doubt, the solicitor who acted for you in the lettings are
best placed to advise you, since he has ready access to the relevant facts,
figures and dates - as well, of course, as knowing the tax law and practice
relating to domestic property letting.
Ask your UK tax office for the free booklet IR20 (Residents and
non-residents: liability to tax in the UK).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
