<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): Portfolio has a price -
Briefcase, Q&amp;A
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
In September 1993, I was given a considerable share portfolio.
1. What tax liability does this entail for the donor and myself?
2. What is the position regarding letting of rooms in a house which is being
part-purchased by a mortgage of some 30 per cent of its value.
Is it necessary to notify the mortgage company that some rooms are being
let, and will the lettings have any implications for insuring the property
and contents?
1. The donor is liable to pay capital gains tax as though he had sold the
shares to you at their respective market values on the day of the gift.
Correspondingly, you will be treated (for CGT purposes) as though you had
bought the shares on that day at the market values. No doubt the donor will
let you have a list of the agreed values after his CGT liability (if any)
has been settled.
There will be no inheritance tax liability unless the donor dies before the
seventh anniversary of the gift. (This reply is based on the assumption that
all the shares are listed on the London Stock Exchange, and that the donor
is resident (and ordinarily resident) in the UK and domiciled in one of its
three constituent countries). 2. You will find that your mortgage agreement
obliges you to notify the lender of any intention to let part of the
property; and you will find that your insurance policy (contents section)
obliges you to notify the insurer before allowing any third party to live in
the house. (We are a little puzzled, however, that you wrote to us, rather
than simply reading the documents).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
