<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Pensions): Why household names can cost you
plenty - Be on guard for big differences in what providers charge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When it comes to selecting a personal pension, relying on a household name
with a good performance track record could prove an expensive mistake. The
amount of your premium deducted in charges not only varies from provider to
provider but can vary greatly between contracts from the same stable.
The latest research from Bacon &amp; Woodrow, a leading actuary and consultant,
shows that Gartmore, Equitable Life, Legal &amp; General and Britannia Life -
all top providers for one or more example combinations of term and premium -
are over-priced for others (see table).
The survey also raises a serious concern about the details financial
institutions provide on their charges. Andrew Warwick-Thompson, head of
partnership pensions at B&amp;W and author of the report, said: 'The annual
management charge, bid/offer spread (the initial charge) on the purchase of
units and administration fees are not the only costs passed on to
policy-holders.
'In most cases, unit-linked funds bear additional costs which are reflected
in the unit price - for example audit fees, dealing commissions, trusteeship
fees, custody fees and stamp duty.' According to Warwick-Thompson, these
costs can add up to the equivalent of an extra 0.5 per cent on the annual
management charge and are most likely to occur where the stated annual
charge appears low.
He pointed out also that these hidden charges will not be revealed under the
rules that come into force on January 1 1995 and require providers to show
prospective clients the management and sales commission costs - an oversight
the regulators should have spotted.
B&amp;W examined 233 managed unit-linked funds, the most popular choice for
investors. Using performance statistics, it eliminated funds that achieved
below-average returns, or were inconsistent or volatile.
As Warwick-Thompson explained: 'The use of past performance statistics is
probably the best guide to gauge future performance - provided it is coupled
with a clear understanding of how past performance was achieved, an
assessment of the investment style of a management team, and a knowledge of
whether the individuals responsible for past performance are still in
place.'
Only funds with a five-year track record and Pounds 20m under management
made it through to the final short-list. Since B&amp;W operates on a fee basis,
it also excluded providers who were not prepared to strip out the commission
costs and re-invest these in the fund. And several funds were eliminated
where the provider's contract imposed penalties on transfer or early
retirement.
The final short-list of 15 funds from 12 providers was: Britannia Life,
Commercial Union, Equitable Life, General Accident, Gartmore, Legal &amp;
General, Lincoln National (three funds), London &amp; Manchester, M&amp;G, Norwich
Union, Standard Life (two funds) and Sun Life.
B&amp;W then calculated reduction in premium (RIP) figures for each fund to find
the most competitive provider for a series of contract terms and premium
levels (see table). RIP analysis shows the effect of charges expressed as a
percentage reduction of each premium paid throughout the term of the policy.
The short-list and tables do not tell the full story, however. Recently, B&amp;W
published a report that predicted the imminent demise of 40 of the 100 life
offices now in business.
Smaller life offices, particularly the mutuals, are vulnerable to take-over
in the post-January 1995 competitive environment. Thus, advisers may not
recommend for long-term investments those offices regarded as take-over
targets.
The results of the survey are based on the terms negotiated by B&amp;W. These
may not be available through other advisers. The Bacon &amp; Woodrow Personal
Pension Handbook and Unit-Linked Survey 1994-94 is available from NTC
Publications Ltd, Farm Road, Henley-on-Thames, Oxfordshire RG9 1EJ (tel:
0491-574 671). Price: Pounds 27.50.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
BEST PERSONAL PENSION PROVIDERS
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
