<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Investing for Income): Bonds that beat the
building societies - Regular incomes, second of a series
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There are many ultra-cautious investors who need a guaranteed income but
want to preserve capital. The two products examined here - pensioners'
guaranteed income bonds from National Savings, and guaranteed income bonds
sold by insurance companies - can provide a higher monthly income than
variable-rate building society accounts.
The income is fixed for five years for pensioners' bonds and three to five
years for most of the insurance company bonds. At the end of the guarantee
period, you get your original capital back - but its real value will have
fallen because of inflation.
To counteract this, those with long-term income needs should protect their
capital against inflation by investing in equities as well.
Those who need short-term income might be interested in a guaranteed income
bond. But they should remember:
National Savings products do not pay commission to advisers, so this could
influence recommendations. But the insurance company bonds pay commission of
between 1 and 2 per cent of the lump sum investment.
National Savings products are backed by the government, but insurance
company bonds are sold mainly by the smaller life offices. Your guarantee is
only as solid as the company backing it, so be on the alert for unknown
companies offering high rates. If a company goes to the wall, only 90 per
cent of your money is covered by the Policyholders Protection Act of 1975.
The level of income on guaranteed bonds is determined by underlying money
market interest rate movements. Clearly, the aim is to fix a deal before
rates start to fall - but are you confident you can predict the direction
they will take when the experts consistently get it wrong?
These are short-term products, but you will be penalised if you withdraw
money early. With pensioners' bonds, you must give 60 days' notice of
withdrawal; during this period, you get no interest. Insurance companies
have similar penalties. While rarely disclosed and virtually impossible to
calculate, they are likely to be punitive.
Tax status
This is a crucial factor. The income from pensioners' bonds is paid gross
but the income from the insurance guaranteed bonds is deemed to be paid net
of basic-rate tax. In theory, this should make the former a clear winner for
non-taxpayers, but the slightly higher income available on the insurance
bonds can offset this tax advantage. Depending on rates at the time,
non-taxpayers should consider both products.
Pensioners' bonds are not attractive for taxpayers, who should choose
insurance bonds if rates are good.
Income level
Rates for pensioners' bonds do not change often and the income level is the
same for any investment between Pounds 500 and Pounds 20,000. Insurance bond
rates change frequently and also vary according to the provider, the term
and the amount invested. The top rate of 8 per cent net quoted in the
fact-file applies to five-year terms where the investment is Pounds 10,000
or more.
Tips from the experts
Michael Bryant, marketing director of Rathbone Brothers, a private client
banking and asset management group, was particularly concerned about the
erosion of the underlying capital associated with these products, and the
gamble on interest rates.
'Investors could be better off shopping around for the best building society
rates and sticking to a maximum notice period of one month,' he said.
'Guaranteed income bonds are sensible only if you have fixed income and
known capital liabilities. Very few people are in this position.'
Andrew Jones, a partner with The David Aaron Partnership, an independent
adviser, added: 'With these guaranteed products the investor and his adviser
have to make a decision based on future interest rate movements.
'We believe the 8 per cent now offered by the insurance guaranteed income
bonds represents good value.
'But if you think a Labour government will be elected in two years and that
interest rates will rise, you might decide to keep your money in a
variable-rate building society account and hope to lock into better
guaranteed rates later.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
TWO OPTIONS FOR SAFETY-FIRST INVESTORS
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Pensioners guaranteed income bonds
Recent net income or yield:
Non-taxpayers:                  7.5%
25% taxpayers:                 5.62%
40% taxpayers:                  4.5%
Key facts: Minimum age 65, minimum investment Pounds 500, maximum
           Pounds 20,000. Sold through the post office, guaranteed
           by the government
Comment:   No capital growth
For more information about National Savings products ask at your local
post office or phone the NS helpline on 0645 645 000
