<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Investing for Income): How to choose the
right fund - Scheherazade Daneshkhu has some suggestions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Anyone who wants to invest in a broad spread of equities through a unit
trust faces the basic choice of investing for 'income' or 'capital growth'.
Unit trusts are divided into different sectors by the Association of Unit
Trusts and Investment Funds - the industry's trade body - which makes it
easier for investors to find their way around the 1,500-odd unit trusts on
offer.
The UK equity income sector might seem a natural place for anyone wanting an
income to place their money. But funds within the sector are very different
and the type you choose depends on your income needs and tax position.
Q. If the funds are all in one sector, presumably they pay out similar
levels of income?
A. No. There is a good deal of variety. Some funds lay the emphasis on
'total return' to provide income and capital growth; they tend to have a
lower yield - or payout - than others which aim to deliver the highest
possible yield. Yields ranged from 1 to 9.9 per cent at the beginning of
November.
Q. I have heard that unit trust managers can charge their annual management
fees to capital instead of income. What effect does this have?
A. Until recently, these charges had to come off the 'profit' or income of
the fund and could not be deducted from the capital base, but new rules
introduced earlier this year allow income trusts to do so. (Capital growth
funds are still not allowed to charge to capital.)
Some unit trust companies including M&amp;G, the largest, are opposed to
charging to capital but others, such as Save &amp; Prosper, HSBC, Invesco,
Schroder and Credit Suisse, are already doing so on some of their funds. The
main effect is to increase the yield and, therefore, income available to the
customer.
Annual management charges tend to be in the region of 1.5 per cent, so a
unit trust with a yield of 5 per cent can, as a result of the change, post
one of 6.5 per cent without altering the composition of the fund.
In practice, unit trust companies which have bought lower-quality stocks for
their high yield, may pass on only part of this increased yield to the
customer and use the rest to buy higher-quality stocks with better capital
growth prospects.
Q. That sounds like good news, so why the opposition?
A. It is good for those seeking as much income as possible, but they should
also be aware that charging to capital can reduce the size of their capital
or constrain its future growth. The danger is that by receiving an increased
payout, investors may think they are getting something for nothing.
M&amp;G's Rachel Medill says: 'No one will be better off in total return terms
by charging to capital. You are not taking charges out of the profit but out
of the base capital, and that is what is providing the income growth.'
Taxpayers, particularly at the higher-rate, should also be careful because
they will be taxed on the 'extra' income.
Q. Can't you pay less tax by choosing to take less income?
A. This is one of the most common investor misunderstandings, according to
Ian Chimes, managing director of Credit Suisse investment funds (UK). 'They
think that if they do not take the income, they will not be taxed on it.' In
fact, it makes no difference if you take the income or choose to have it
re-invested - it will be paid to you (or re-invested) net of basic-rate tax.
Higher-rate taxpayers must pay the difference.
The exception is when the unit trust is bought within a tax-free personal
equity plan. 'The Pep allows an investor to re-invest income gross until it
is needed when distributions can be paid, again, gross,' says Mike Webb,
sales and marketing director of Prolific Unit Trust Managers. 'Many income
unit trust Peps are sold on the basis of pre-retirement planning precisely
because for this reason.'
Q. How do I re-invest income if I do not want to take it?
A. If you want to re-invest income, it is best to choose an income fund
offering accumulation as well as income units. Accumulation units
automatically invest the income generated by the fund to buy more assets,
which pushes up the price of the units.
Income units, as the name implies, pay out income at set dates. If you try
to re-invest it, the fund buys more units, so the number you hold will
increase. But Clive Boothman, managing director of Schroder Unit Trusts,
says there is a disadvantage: 'If a fund has only income units, re-investing
is perfectly possible but may incur front-end charges which are absent when
re-investment takes place in accumulation units.'
Some funds will waive the front-end charge but you might still end up paying
a bit more this way because of the spread - the difference between the
purchase and selling price - of the underlying assets. You can tell if an
income fund has accumulation units by looking at the FT's managed funds
pages. Q. I am a higher-rate taxpayer - is there a more tax-efficient way
for me to take income from unit trusts?
A. Yes. Less than 0.5 per cent of the population pays capital gains tax
while most pays income tax. Yet, you can make up to Pounds 5,800 of gains
tax-free, thanks to the annual capital gains tax allowance.
So it is a good idea to try to take income in the form of capital gain. You
cannot take returns solely as capital gain in an income unit trust because
(as described above) the pay-out is treated as income for tax purposes.
The alternative is to invest in a capital growth unit trust and to sell
units periodically to provide yourself with an income. The gains will be
tax-free, as long as you do not exceed the CGT allowance.
Some capital growth trusts have a yield. Try to avoid these because the
income will be taxed at 40 per cent (as a higher rate taxpayer), regardless
of whether it is taken or re-invested. Chimes says many higher-rate
taxpayers prefer Far East or US trusts which pay no income, for this reason.
But take care with this method - if you withdraw too much capital, the
chance for future growth will be damaged.
</TEXT>
